</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ucobra102.showPublicProfile?language=EN>cobra102</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/16/02 4:25:29 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1209.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_supermad.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Signs of a bad cleric</span><hr size=1> Celestial Healing is a nice heal used properly as has been described. Unfortunately the low aggro side of it has an irresistible attraction for some clerics and I think this is what makes them use it instead of better heals.<br>
<br>
The same is true of the lower level Celestial Remedy but without the excuse of long cast times for other heals. If you are fighting a single pull at that level and the cleric uses Celestial Remedy they are battle-shy. I was told of a cleric who refused to use GHeal because he might get aggro, and let people die because Healing was not enough.<br>
<br>
As far as &quot;Battle-Cleric&quot; is concerned there are only two situations I will melee:<br>
Full Mana and health all round and a chance to catch up some skill, <br>
or <br>
OOM, no chance to med, and If we're going down it may as well be fighting.<br>
<br>
A cleric who melees when they could med and then calls &quot;OOM&quot; is a very bad cleric.<br>
<br>
I liked the comment about Clerics stunning. I am often having to explain how Stunning saves mana by not needing heals as much when someone tells me to &quot;Stop nuking&quot;. <br>
<br>
One thing that always amuses me is that places like Unrest are always described in the guides as &quot;Great for Clerics&quot; because of our mana-efficient undead nukes, and yet people you group with still don't want the cleric nuking <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> .<br>
<br>
I agree with the praise for high level Paladin healers. At low levels however they can be a royal pain. The number of times I have had a paladin join a group and immediately assume that they are prime buffer/healer without even asking. I usually end up fighting with my own buffs down because I would rather buff the tank than myself so I find I suddenly have Courage cast on me and that the same Paladin proceeds to burn mana casting his buffs on the entire group. I even had one who would stop fighting to heal. As soon as anyone was even half a bubble down he would step back and &quot;Healing &lt;xxx&gt; with the light of Mithaniel Marr&quot;, Light Healing would go in. I just could not get him to stop.<br>
<br>
I think the Druid healing versus Cleric healing is a paper tiger. A good druid/shaman is better than a bad cleric any day. The only issue is that these guys have offensive spells clerics can only dream of so they have much better things to be doing if grouped with a cleric than compete for the healing. If a druid/shaman insists on planting a heal while I am still waiting for the tank to go down far enough to need GHeal or SHeal from me then my role in the group is void. To leave them to heal while I become a second-rank nuker is sublimely silly. (Please note I am not talking about patch-healing while CHeal goes in.)<br>
<br>
